WEBVTT

00:01.330 --> 00:03.710
♪ One, two, three, four, unh! ♪

00:03.710 --> 00:05.330
♪ Whoo-o-o-o ♪

00:08.120 --> 00:10.580
Meredith: Pharmaceuticals
are designed to mimic

00:10.580 --> 00:13.290
the body's
natural brain chemicals --

00:13.290 --> 00:15.210
the ones
that make you feel good,

00:15.210 --> 00:17.880
make you feel better,
make you feel unstoppable.

00:17.880 --> 00:21.120
[ Monitor beeping ]

00:21.120 --> 00:22.540
3-0 tie, please.

00:24.210 --> 00:27.210
♪ In the back of my mind,
I was losing it ♪

00:27.210 --> 00:28.710
How long do you think
it'll take

00:28.710 --> 00:31.250
before I'm ready to do
a 24-hour surgery?

00:31.250 --> 00:33.790
I'm not sure that's
a healthy life goal, Qadri.

00:33.790 --> 00:35.420
[ Crunching ]

00:35.420 --> 00:37.000
Hey.

00:37.000 --> 00:38.580
What's going on?

00:38.580 --> 00:41.290
Mer's doing a pancreas-sparing
total duodenectomy

00:41.290 --> 00:42.750
in a frozen abdomen.

00:42.750 --> 00:44.080
Oh. It got moved
from yesterday?

00:44.080 --> 00:45.920
No, she started it
yesterday.

00:45.920 --> 00:47.830
Five more hours, and she's gonna
break the hospital's record

00:47.830 --> 00:49.040
for the longest surgery.

00:49.040 --> 00:51.120
You think it's gonna take
five more hours?

00:51.120 --> 00:53.210
Well, I mean, with the adhesions
and the scar tissue,

00:53.210 --> 00:55.620
it's taking her longer,
so, yeah.

00:55.620 --> 00:56.620
She can beat the record.

00:56.620 --> 00:58.580
Feel a little better?
No.

00:58.580 --> 01:00.790
I mean, yeah, she gets awards
and prizes and all that,

01:00.790 --> 01:02.880
but I get to be chief,
so we're good.

01:02.880 --> 01:04.830
[ Laughs ]

01:04.830 --> 01:07.420
They make it in a lab and put
it in a pill for pain relief,

01:07.420 --> 01:10.290
giving you the high
your body creates naturally

01:10.290 --> 01:11.920
anytime you're doing
something you love.

01:11.920 --> 01:13.330
[ Exhales sharply ]

01:13.330 --> 01:14.710
Helm.

01:14.710 --> 01:16.250
You want to tap out?

01:16.250 --> 01:17.420
No, thank you.

01:17.420 --> 01:18.880
DeLuca?
No, thank you. I'm good.

01:20.790 --> 01:22.710
[ Thud ]

01:22.710 --> 01:24.460
Think he could
use a break, though.

01:26.250 --> 01:29.040
[ Whirring ]

01:29.040 --> 01:30.670
When I said
"breakfast,"

01:30.670 --> 01:33.500
I meant more of a place
where we sit,

01:33.500 --> 01:37.420
someone takes our order,
there's less...lion jaws.

01:37.420 --> 01:40.790
No. Um...
pointed reduction clamp.

01:40.790 --> 01:42.830
I let interns assist
on hip replacements

01:42.830 --> 01:44.000
once they're prepared.

01:44.000 --> 01:46.330
I don't dish out
special favors.

01:46.330 --> 01:48.000
[ Whirring stops ]
At work.

01:50.540 --> 01:52.210
[ Device clatters ]
Neck osteotomy's done.

01:52.210 --> 01:53.460
Now we got to get into
the femoral canal.

01:53.460 --> 01:54.460
What's the next step?

01:54.460 --> 01:57.460
Okay,
first, I'll do a ream.

01:57.460 --> 01:59.580
And what would you use?

01:59.580 --> 02:02.210
I think
the Christmas Tree Reamer.

02:04.210 --> 02:06.790
[ Whirring ]

02:10.880 --> 02:13.830
Let's do actual breakfast
on Thursday.

02:13.830 --> 02:14.790
I'll make French toast.

02:20.620 --> 02:21.920
Maggie: [ Laughs ]

02:21.920 --> 02:23.750
Why are you holding
toilet paper?

02:23.750 --> 02:25.250
It's the most important
camping supply.

02:26.750 --> 02:28.580
Oh, God.
Why's your face like that?

02:28.580 --> 02:29.580
I, uh --

02:29.580 --> 02:31.790
O-Our weekend away
is camping?

02:31.790 --> 02:34.460
Yeah. Babe, what did
you think Glen Rock was?

02:34.460 --> 02:36.250
"Sounds fancy,
but I deserve it"?

02:36.250 --> 02:37.710
I mean, of all the campsites
I went to,

02:37.710 --> 02:38.920
yeah, I guess
it's the fanciest.

02:38.920 --> 02:40.040
It did have
running water.

02:40.040 --> 02:41.290
But no toilet paper,
so no --

02:41.290 --> 02:42.710
Toilets.

02:42.710 --> 02:44.420
Okay, so, right.
Where do we go --

02:44.420 --> 02:45.710
I packed a small shovel.

02:45.710 --> 02:47.580
And there are these really nice
rocks. They're great.

02:47.580 --> 02:50.920
You just kind of move over them,
kind of, as you...

02:50.920 --> 02:52.710
Look, it's camping,
babe.

02:52.710 --> 02:54.120
We're going camping.

02:54.120 --> 02:55.330
[ Laughs nervously ]
Are we, though?

02:55.330 --> 02:57.040
Ohh!
You're gonna love it!

03:02.040 --> 03:05.420
This is Tom Koracick?
The one who works here?

03:05.420 --> 03:07.790
I was surprised, too.
But it's, you know --

03:07.790 --> 03:10.330
I don't know.
It's new, and it's --

03:10.330 --> 03:12.670
it's just kind of...
amazing.

03:12.670 --> 03:15.460
Look, I definitely
didn't expect to be dating

03:15.460 --> 03:18.380
at 30 weeks pregnant,
but he's kind and fun,

03:18.380 --> 03:20.540
and he's kinda wow.

03:20.540 --> 03:22.330
Huh.
[ Laughing ] I know.

03:22.330 --> 03:24.710
[ Tires screeching ]
How about you and Ben,
now that he's back home?

03:24.710 --> 03:25.790
Watch out!

03:25.790 --> 03:28.040
Slow down!
This is a hospital!

03:28.040 --> 03:29.250
Man: Get out!
Go, go, go!

03:29.250 --> 03:30.120
Oh, my --
Go, go, go, go!

03:30.120 --> 03:31.000
[ Engine revs ]

03:31.000 --> 03:32.580
Hey, Bailey,
pinpoint pupils!

03:32.580 --> 03:35.420
Yeah. Get some Narcan,
a crash cart, and some O2.

03:35.420 --> 03:36.750
I think
we got an OD.

03:45.080 --> 03:46.920
[ Indistinct conversations ]

03:46.920 --> 03:48.540
I thought
you'd be in O.R. 3.

03:48.540 --> 03:49.960
I've been busy.

03:49.960 --> 03:52.460
This boy's buddies almost ran me
over in the ambulance bay.

03:52.460 --> 03:53.790
Tossed him
out of the car.

03:53.790 --> 03:55.170
Opioid overdose.

03:55.170 --> 03:57.380
Why? What's going on
in O.R. 3?

03:57.380 --> 03:59.420
Grey's been in surgery
since yesterday.

03:59.420 --> 04:01.120
Quite a crowd.

04:01.120 --> 04:02.620
Bailey,
we got two more.

04:02.620 --> 04:04.120
Two more overdoses?

04:04.120 --> 04:06.380
Mm-hmm. Jerry and Paula.
Regulars.

04:06.380 --> 04:08.290
Always shooting up
in the park down the street.

04:08.290 --> 04:09.880
They usually wake up
with one dose of Narcan

04:09.880 --> 04:11.080
and then
refuse treatment,

04:11.080 --> 04:12.210
but I've already given them
three doses,

04:12.210 --> 04:13.670
and they're not
responding.

04:13.670 --> 04:15.790
There's a bad batch
of something out there.
Okay.

04:15.790 --> 04:18.710
Man on P.A.:
Attention, all units.
We've reached Code Red status.

04:18.710 --> 04:20.580
Any available unit, please
report to Meridien Park

04:20.580 --> 04:22.580
for multiple
suspected overdose events.

04:22.580 --> 04:24.170
Looks like I'll be
seeing a lot of you today.

04:24.170 --> 04:25.210
[ Sighs ]

04:25.210 --> 04:27.170
Okay, listen up.

04:27.170 --> 04:29.790
This is gonna be
an all-hands-on-deck situation.

04:29.790 --> 04:31.580
Let's page on-call personnel.

04:31.580 --> 04:33.920
Let's make sure that we got
all the Narcan from the pharmacy

04:33.920 --> 04:35.420
to reverse the opioids.

04:35.420 --> 04:37.750
We need to be prepared
for secondary injuries

04:37.750 --> 04:39.420
and side effects.

04:39.420 --> 04:41.420
Wait a minute.
Where are all my residents?

04:41.420 --> 04:42.960
Richard:
Uh, they're in Grey's gallery.

04:42.960 --> 04:43.960
I'll make sure
they get down here.

04:43.960 --> 04:44.960
Okay.

04:44.960 --> 04:46.580
What about Hunt?

04:46.580 --> 04:48.290
Um, he's, uh...

04:48.290 --> 04:50.080
[ Indistinct talking ]

04:50.080 --> 04:52.620
He's saying goodbye to Leo.
Betty's parents are taking him.

04:52.620 --> 04:54.120
Oh. Um...

04:54.120 --> 04:56.750
I'm sorry to hear about that,
but this is a mass OD.

04:57.960 --> 05:00.290
Yep. Okay.
We'll page him.

05:00.290 --> 05:03.710
[ Birds chirping ]

05:03.710 --> 05:05.960
Get your shoe on.

05:05.960 --> 05:07.710
Okay.
Get your shoe on.

05:07.710 --> 05:10.000
Your mom got this for him.
Do you want to keep it or --

05:10.000 --> 05:11.750
No, no.
That's his favorite.

05:15.460 --> 05:18.210
We were gonna -- We were gonna
watch him grow up.

05:18.210 --> 05:19.500
We were gonna
teach him so many things.

05:19.500 --> 05:20.920
[ Doorbell rings ]

05:22.710 --> 05:24.710
Well...

05:24.710 --> 05:26.790
Listen.

05:26.790 --> 05:27.790
I, um...

05:27.790 --> 05:28.960
[ Laughs ]

05:28.960 --> 05:30.500
I hope you play soccer.

05:30.500 --> 05:31.500
[ Laughs ]

05:31.500 --> 05:32.500
[ Cries ]

05:32.500 --> 05:33.880
I hope
you love your life.

05:33.880 --> 05:36.750
Wait, wait. Yours makes mine
sound shallow.

05:36.750 --> 05:38.250
Yeah. You should
probably go again.

05:38.250 --> 05:39.960
[ Doorbell rings ]
Yeah. Um...

05:39.960 --> 05:41.790
Listen.

05:41.790 --> 05:43.790
[ Breathes deeply ]

05:46.250 --> 05:48.080
I'm always gonna be
rooting for you.

05:48.080 --> 05:50.290
[ Doorbell rings ]

05:50.290 --> 05:51.460
[ Knock on door ]

05:51.460 --> 05:52.460
Okay.

05:52.460 --> 05:53.580
Ready?

05:53.580 --> 05:55.290
No.

05:55.290 --> 05:57.580
But they're good people, Owen,
and they love him.

05:57.580 --> 05:58.920
He will be loved.

06:01.460 --> 06:02.710
Hey.

06:04.920 --> 06:05.920
[ Clears throat ]

06:05.920 --> 06:07.210
Come in.

06:09.120 --> 06:10.120
[ Door closes ]

06:11.670 --> 06:13.170
[ Sighs ]

06:13.170 --> 06:15.830
So, uh...may I?

06:15.830 --> 06:17.540
Oh. Uh, sorry.

06:17.540 --> 06:18.420
Yeah. Here.

06:19.790 --> 06:21.080
Hi!

06:21.080 --> 06:22.830
[ Fusses ]
Ohh!

06:22.830 --> 06:24.670
When he gets fussy like that,
he's usually just hungry.

06:24.670 --> 06:25.920
We've raised one
before.
It's okay.

06:25.920 --> 06:28.000
[ Cellphone buzzes ]
Right.

06:28.000 --> 06:30.250
E.R. 911.
All hands on deck.

06:30.250 --> 06:33.580
So, we are, uh...
very grateful to you both.

06:33.580 --> 06:35.380
I have to go.
Owen --

06:35.380 --> 06:37.750
Listen, it's a massive
incoming trauma. I have to go.

06:37.750 --> 06:39.670
[ Leo crying ]

06:39.670 --> 06:41.500
I'll just,
um...

06:41.500 --> 06:42.960
[ Door closes ]

06:42.960 --> 06:45.210
Do you want to feed him
while I finish packing him up?

06:45.210 --> 06:46.210
Yeah,
that'd be great.

06:46.210 --> 06:48.460
Whoopsie!

06:48.460 --> 06:51.620
Whoa, whoa, whoa!
Okay, everybody slow down.

06:51.620 --> 06:54.620
Speak to your team calmly, get
what they need, and handle it.

06:54.620 --> 06:57.000
With this many people,
communication is key.

06:57.000 --> 06:58.580
What do you got?
He was responding
until about two minutes ago,

06:58.580 --> 07:00.960
when he started
hypoventilating again.

07:00.960 --> 07:02.880
Get him
on a Narcan drip.

07:02.880 --> 07:05.380
Bailey, how's it going?

07:05.380 --> 07:07.120
It's worse outside
than it is in here.

07:07.120 --> 07:08.710
And too many teenagers.

07:08.710 --> 07:10.750
I'm aware that I sound
like my mother,

07:10.750 --> 07:12.670
but is the world going to Hell
in a handbasket?

07:12.670 --> 07:13.750
[ Rapid beeping ]

07:13.750 --> 07:15.330
Uh, 0.4 of Narcan.

07:15.330 --> 07:16.710
All right.
Bailey, you got this?

07:16.710 --> 07:17.670
I'm gonna go
to the ambulance bay

07:17.670 --> 07:18.790
and see if I can get it
under control.

07:18.790 --> 07:20.040
Teddy, I'll do it.

07:20.040 --> 07:21.210
Owen.
Look, I'm sorry.

07:21.210 --> 07:23.040
I-I wasn't
gonna page you, but --

07:23.040 --> 07:24.540
No, no, no.
Better here than at home.

07:24.540 --> 07:25.960
Okay.

07:27.580 --> 07:29.170
Hey.

07:29.170 --> 07:30.500
People are dropping like flies
all over the park.

07:30.500 --> 07:31.620
Never seen
anything like it.

07:31.620 --> 07:32.920
How many ODs
have been called in?

07:32.920 --> 07:34.710
[ Sighs ]
50 and counting.

07:36.960 --> 07:40.250
[ Indistinct talking,
sirens wailing ]

07:40.250 --> 07:41.710
Whoa.

07:41.710 --> 07:45.670
♪♪

07:45.670 --> 07:52.500
♪♪

07:57.960 --> 08:00.420
Hey, everybody! Listen up!
Here's how this is gonna go.

08:00.420 --> 08:02.500
Three ambulances
are gonna pull up.

08:02.500 --> 08:04.500
When the patients are offloaded,
they're gonna pull out,

08:04.500 --> 08:05.960
and then the next three
are gonna come in.

08:05.960 --> 08:08.670
We're gonna set up
a triage area,

08:08.670 --> 08:10.830
where we're gonna assess
each ambulance

08:10.830 --> 08:13.250
and mark them
with the appropriate tag.

08:13.250 --> 08:16.000
Red tags get priority
for the E.R.

08:16.000 --> 08:18.380
Walking wounded will
be shown to the clinic,

08:18.380 --> 08:19.580
where they're gonna
be evaluated.

08:19.580 --> 08:20.580
Thank you.
[ Feedback ]

08:20.580 --> 08:21.500
Thank you.

08:21.500 --> 08:22.540
Let's go.

08:24.380 --> 08:26.830
Meredith: Helm, tell me
about the SMA first approach.

08:26.830 --> 08:28.040
[ Strained ]
You, uh, dissect out

08:28.040 --> 08:30.830
the entire
superior mesenteric artery

08:30.830 --> 08:33.880
to, uh, evaluate for any...
tumor invasion.

08:33.880 --> 08:35.380
Helm, are you in pain?

08:35.380 --> 08:36.880
No.

08:36.880 --> 08:38.460
I, uh...

08:38.460 --> 08:41.250
I just, uh, shouldn't have had
so much coffee.

08:41.250 --> 08:43.000
Well, then go.
No. I can hold it.

08:43.000 --> 08:44.540
If you can, I can.

08:46.120 --> 08:47.500
Did she have
her bladder stapled?

08:47.500 --> 08:48.960
That's not
the hard part --

08:48.960 --> 08:50.500
the achy legs,
the sore feet,

08:50.500 --> 08:52.420
the cramping back,
or the bladder.

08:52.420 --> 08:54.170
No, the hard part is that
this surgery doesn't get easier

08:54.170 --> 08:55.750
as it goes on --
it gets harder.

08:55.750 --> 08:58.290
And her eyes and her instincts
will need to be sharper

08:58.290 --> 09:01.210
when she finishes
than when she started.

09:01.210 --> 09:02.540
And that was yesterday.

09:02.540 --> 09:03.920
Do you think
she's part robot?

09:03.920 --> 09:05.960
I can hear you.

09:05.960 --> 09:07.670
I'm...so sorry.

09:07.670 --> 09:09.460
Helm, just go.
Go update the family.

09:09.460 --> 09:11.120
Tell them
that he's doing great.

09:11.120 --> 09:12.960
And then go see
what you can do in the pit.

09:12.960 --> 09:14.210
Thank you!
Sorry. Thank you!

09:18.460 --> 09:20.460
Hey! Dr. Hays wants to know
if he can still do that surgery.

09:20.460 --> 09:22.540
Not if it's elective.
I want those O.R.s free.

09:22.540 --> 09:23.750
Have you ever seen
anything like this?

09:23.750 --> 09:24.960
No. And of course
it happens on a day

09:24.960 --> 09:26.710
that Mer sets
a new surgical record.

09:26.710 --> 09:28.210
I mean, I want to be there
to cheer her on.

09:28.210 --> 09:30.460
She has DeLuca
to cheer her on.

09:30.460 --> 09:31.670
Well, that's not a thing.
Pretty sure that's a thing.

09:31.670 --> 09:32.880
Wendy: Truman!

09:32.880 --> 09:34.420
Truman?

09:34.420 --> 09:36.460
Ma'am, are you okay?
My son -- Truman.

09:36.460 --> 09:37.920
He's three years old --

09:37.920 --> 09:39.540
He has blond hair, he's wearing
a blue shirt, I think --

09:39.540 --> 09:40.580
All right,
we'll call security --

09:40.580 --> 09:41.670
I talked
to the police.

09:41.670 --> 09:43.250
The police are
at the park, looking.

09:43.250 --> 09:45.120
We were at the park,
playing,

09:45.120 --> 09:46.290
and suddenly
there were ambulances

09:46.290 --> 09:47.380
and police cars
everywhere,

09:47.380 --> 09:48.790
and I went to see
what was going on,

09:48.790 --> 09:50.460
and then
when I turned around...

09:50.460 --> 09:51.460
[ Voice breaking ]
...Truman was gone,

09:51.460 --> 09:53.500
and then, uh --

09:53.500 --> 09:55.120
Anyway, the police
are looking in the park,

09:55.120 --> 09:56.500
and so I thought
I would come here

09:56.500 --> 09:57.880
and see if an ambulance person
or a fireman --

09:57.880 --> 09:59.040
W-What's your name?

09:59.040 --> 10:01.210
Wendy.
Wendy, look,
we're gonna help you.

10:01.210 --> 10:03.040
Jo, can you take her --
I'll take her to security,
see if he's here.

10:03.040 --> 10:05.170
Do you have a picture
of him?
Yes. Yes.

10:05.170 --> 10:06.580
Maggie: Okay, I'll make sure
she has a tele bed

10:06.580 --> 10:08.420
to monitor
for arrhythmias.

10:08.420 --> 10:09.960
And I'll be out of town
this weekend,

10:09.960 --> 10:11.420
but I'll have Parker check
for her electrolytes

10:11.420 --> 10:13.040
and cardiac markers,

10:13.040 --> 10:15.420
and you just, you know, call me
if you see anything unusual.

10:15.420 --> 10:16.250
All right.

10:16.250 --> 10:18.170
If calls can
even go through.

10:18.170 --> 10:20.170
I might be
completely off the grid.

10:20.170 --> 10:21.830
You going to the moon?

10:21.830 --> 10:23.120
I'm going camping.

10:23.120 --> 10:24.500
Why?

10:24.500 --> 10:26.710
'Cause Jackson loves camping
and I love Jackson.

10:26.710 --> 10:29.040
I love Ben, but I don't love
fantasy basketball.

10:29.040 --> 10:30.460
Therefore,
I don't participate.

10:30.460 --> 10:33.880
I'm going camping, Bailey,
and I am going to like it.

10:33.880 --> 10:35.000
Are you, though?

10:36.250 --> 10:38.750
[ Indistinct conversations ]

10:38.750 --> 10:40.330
All right, Qadri,
so, we're definitely looking

10:40.330 --> 10:41.880
at a shooter's abscess.

10:41.880 --> 10:43.880
I need to you make sure
he's got plenty of antibiotics

10:43.880 --> 10:45.500
and get a full washout
in the O.R.

10:45.500 --> 10:47.330
And look,
I know it smells bad,

10:47.330 --> 10:48.960
but breathe out of your mouth
or something

10:48.960 --> 10:51.000
so you don't look
so overtly disgusted.

10:53.670 --> 10:55.620
Mr. Frazier's prepped
for his hip replacement,

10:55.620 --> 10:57.540
and Schmitt's been crushing
the saw bones sessions,

10:57.540 --> 10:58.790
so he'll assist.

10:58.790 --> 11:00.670
That's great, but Schmitt's
gonna have to wait.

11:00.670 --> 11:02.880
But his technique's flawless,
and I'll be there --

11:02.880 --> 11:05.500
I see the butterflies
floating around between you two,

11:05.500 --> 11:07.330
and that's cool, but try
to see past them long enough

11:07.330 --> 11:09.580
to notice the flood of patients
around you.

11:09.580 --> 11:11.120
I postponed
Mr. Frazier's surgery.

11:11.120 --> 11:12.420
It's all hands on deck
with trauma.

11:12.420 --> 11:15.460
Got it.
This unlucky lady
not only OD'd,

11:15.460 --> 11:17.750
she broke both of her arms
when she fell.

11:17.750 --> 11:20.290
She needs to go to the O.R.
Schmitt can assist with that.

11:20.290 --> 11:22.170
And tell
the anesthesiologist

11:22.170 --> 11:23.830
she's had four doses
of Narcan.

11:23.830 --> 11:25.620
Thank you so much, sir.
I won't let you down.

11:25.620 --> 11:27.040
I am ready and prepared
and --

11:27.040 --> 11:29.120
Show me,
don't tell me, Schmitt.

11:30.670 --> 11:32.120
Interns.
Am I right?

11:32.120 --> 11:34.210
[ Scoffs ]

11:34.210 --> 11:35.620
No offense.

11:35.620 --> 11:37.620
None taken.

11:37.620 --> 11:38.880
Out of your mouth,
please.

11:38.880 --> 11:40.880
[ Breathes deeply ]

11:40.880 --> 11:42.750
[ Indistinct talking,
sirens wailing ]

11:46.540 --> 11:47.830
Apneic at the scene
with erratic rhythms --

11:47.830 --> 11:49.580
last BP, 80 over 40.

11:49.580 --> 11:52.210
Got one patient responsive
after two doses of Narcan

11:52.210 --> 11:53.670
and another one
with decreased mentation

11:53.670 --> 11:54.880
but responsive
and talking.

11:54.880 --> 11:56.330
[ Rapid beeping ]

11:56.330 --> 11:57.380
He lost his pulse.
Starting CPR.

11:57.380 --> 11:58.960
Helm, your two sound good
to go to the clinic,

11:58.960 --> 12:00.460
but keep an eye on them.

12:00.460 --> 12:01.960
Yes, sir.
Let's get them inside.
Come on.

12:03.750 --> 12:06.000
[ Panting ]

12:06.000 --> 12:07.250
[ Weakly ]
What's happening?

12:07.250 --> 12:08.330
Linus:
Is s-she gonna be okay?

12:08.330 --> 12:09.670
Get these two
into the clinic.

12:09.670 --> 12:11.120
Is she -- Betty!

12:11.120 --> 12:12.120
Betty!

12:16.330 --> 12:17.380
Meredith: Unh! 5-0.

12:17.380 --> 12:18.380
4-0.

12:18.380 --> 12:25.330
♪♪

12:25.330 --> 12:27.080
[ Cheering ]

12:28.580 --> 12:29.920
What happened?
You did it.

12:29.920 --> 12:31.750
No, I haven't finished
the anastomosis

12:31.750 --> 12:33.330
or the lymphadenectomy.

12:33.330 --> 12:34.710
Suture scissors, Bokhee.

12:34.710 --> 12:36.210
Mered--

12:36.210 --> 12:38.420
Dr. Grey, you just beat
the hospital record

12:38.420 --> 12:39.920
for the longest
single surgery.

12:39.920 --> 12:42.670
Yeah.
I guess I did.

12:42.670 --> 12:44.170
[ Sighs ]

12:44.170 --> 12:45.500
Damn it.

12:45.500 --> 12:46.790
What?

12:46.790 --> 12:48.670
That just means that I'm gonna
want to break it again.

12:48.670 --> 12:50.040
[ Scoffs ]

12:50.040 --> 12:52.620
Okay, let's get ready
with some lap pads.

12:52.620 --> 12:56.080
And, uh, Bokhee, someone should
update the family.

12:56.080 --> 12:57.830
Okay. I'm gonna tell them
their son's being saved

12:57.830 --> 12:59.670
by a surgical legend.

12:59.670 --> 13:00.880
Okay, don't do that.

13:00.880 --> 13:02.210
Surgical superhero?

13:02.210 --> 13:03.620
No.
Wonder Woman?

13:03.620 --> 13:05.250
Yeah! Perfect.

13:05.250 --> 13:06.250
[ Laughs ]

13:06.250 --> 13:07.250
Thank you, Bokhee.

13:07.250 --> 13:08.500
Whoo!

13:08.500 --> 13:10.580
You are.

13:10.580 --> 13:13.210
Okay, now observe
the scaphoid carefully.

13:13.210 --> 13:15.040
What's the usual
point of entry?

13:15.040 --> 13:16.920
The distal pole.

13:16.920 --> 13:18.710
But wait.
There's a humpback deformity.

13:18.710 --> 13:20.080
Exactly.

13:21.790 --> 13:23.330
Can you imagine...

13:23.330 --> 13:25.330
[ Whirring ]
...wanting something so badly

13:25.330 --> 13:28.380
that you'd be willing to
break both your arms to get it?

13:28.380 --> 13:30.120
Well, she didn't mean
to break her arms.

13:30.120 --> 13:31.380
Yeah, I know.
I'm just --

13:31.380 --> 13:32.750
I broke
both my arms once.

13:32.750 --> 13:34.330
You did?

13:34.330 --> 13:36.290
Couldn't wipe my own butt
all summer. It was the worst.

13:36.290 --> 13:39.120
But the new X-Men comic
was coming out,

13:39.120 --> 13:41.040
and I had to have it.

13:41.040 --> 13:44.460
Like, had to be first in line
because, in my world,

13:44.460 --> 13:47.500
that was the only thing
worth bragging about.

13:47.500 --> 13:49.170
Fell off your bike?

13:49.170 --> 13:52.500
Flipped over the handlebars --
one block from the store.

13:52.500 --> 13:56.460
I got two months in casts,
three months of PT.

13:56.460 --> 13:59.120
And Robbie Freaking Krimefelt
got bragging rights.

13:59.120 --> 14:00.620
So yeah.

14:00.620 --> 14:04.620
I get wanting something so bad
you'd be willing to --

14:04.620 --> 14:06.330
Whoa. You just...

14:08.580 --> 14:09.750
All right.

14:09.750 --> 14:11.670
She's all good.

14:11.670 --> 14:13.710
And with no hands to shoot up
for the next three months,

14:13.710 --> 14:15.710
hopefully, she'll actually
manage to detox.

14:17.380 --> 14:19.460
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Mahoney to the E.R.

14:19.460 --> 14:21.330
Dr. Mahoney to the E.R.

14:21.330 --> 14:22.540
Hey.

14:22.540 --> 14:23.830
Tell me
she found that kid.

14:23.830 --> 14:25.880
No.
Security's on it.

14:25.880 --> 14:28.040
I'm worried about her.
Her BP's through the roof.

14:28.040 --> 14:29.380
She is so scared.

14:29.380 --> 14:31.120
Man: Excuse me.

14:31.120 --> 14:34.460
I found him in the park --
kind of shook up.

14:34.460 --> 14:35.960
Truman!

14:35.960 --> 14:37.790
I'm gonna --

14:37.790 --> 14:39.250
Mommy!

14:39.250 --> 14:40.460
Alex: Thank you.

14:40.460 --> 14:41.750
I saw him wandering,

14:41.750 --> 14:44.170
and I thought, well,
everybody's coming here.

14:44.170 --> 14:46.620
Uh...yeah.

14:46.620 --> 14:48.580
Let -- Let us get you some food
and some shoes, maybe.

14:48.580 --> 14:50.000
No. Unh-unh.

14:50.000 --> 14:52.210
No, please. We got to
take a look at those feet.

14:52.210 --> 14:53.710
Uh, Qadri, could you help
this gentleman?

14:53.710 --> 14:54.920
Yeah.

14:57.380 --> 14:59.580
So, she's all right, then?
That lady?

14:59.580 --> 15:01.330
Oh, yeah. She's --
She's fine, thanks to you.

15:01.330 --> 15:02.540
She was scared
out of her mind.

15:02.540 --> 15:04.380
No, I mean
from the park.

15:04.380 --> 15:06.620
I saw her passed out
on the bench out there

15:06.620 --> 15:08.460
with the rest
of them junkies.

15:08.460 --> 15:14.500
♪♪

15:14.500 --> 15:17.120
[ Sirens wails,
indistinct talking ]

15:23.830 --> 15:25.210
I want to go.

15:25.210 --> 15:26.580
Can we go?
Can you get our clothes?

15:26.580 --> 15:28.670
Okay, yeah. Sure. I just --
I want to make sure you're okay.

15:28.670 --> 15:29.750
I want to go.

15:29.750 --> 15:31.580
I don't want Amelia
to see me here.

15:31.580 --> 15:33.210
I-I don't want to put her
through that again.

15:33.210 --> 15:34.620
O-Okay.
Linus, please, can we --

15:34.620 --> 15:36.170
[ Gasping ]

15:36.170 --> 15:37.540
Hey. Hey!

15:37.540 --> 15:39.120
Hey! Help!
I need help!

15:39.120 --> 15:40.920
Hey. It's okay.

15:40.920 --> 15:42.580
She was just talking.

15:42.580 --> 15:44.170
She wasn't complaining
of anything when she came in.

15:44.170 --> 15:45.420
Well,
she's complaining now.

15:45.420 --> 15:46.460
It hurts!

15:46.460 --> 15:47.580
What did she take?
I need to know.

15:47.580 --> 15:49.210
Meth.

15:49.210 --> 15:50.750
We smoked some meth before
the batch of pills came 'round.

15:50.750 --> 15:51.750
280 over 145.

15:51.750 --> 15:53.000
Okay,
I need a gurney!

15:53.000 --> 15:55.210
[ Indistinct talking ]

15:58.960 --> 16:00.170
Out of my way.

16:00.170 --> 16:01.250
Out of my way!

16:01.250 --> 16:04.880
♪♪

16:04.880 --> 16:06.420
[ Indistinct talking ]

16:06.420 --> 16:08.420
I got a hypertensive
emergency here.

16:08.420 --> 16:09.620
Took meth and opioids

16:09.620 --> 16:11.460
and whatever
they were laced with.

16:11.460 --> 16:12.750
Clear a trauma room now!

16:12.750 --> 16:13.920
♪♪

16:19.170 --> 16:21.500
Owen: 7-0 tube.

16:21.500 --> 16:23.120
Link:
Helm said she was stable when
she landed. This just happened.

16:23.120 --> 16:24.290
Linus: What's happening?
Is she okay?

16:24.290 --> 16:25.170
Who's that?
No idea. Boyfriend?

16:25.170 --> 16:26.460
Get him out of here.
I've got this.

16:26.460 --> 16:28.830
No! I need to be with Betty,
all right?

16:28.830 --> 16:30.670
I love her.
I love her. Please.
Get him out of here!

16:30.670 --> 16:32.540
I need to be with her!
She's afraid to be alone!

16:32.540 --> 16:34.460
Dude, let me help you.
Let them help her.

16:34.460 --> 16:35.580
Go.

16:35.580 --> 16:36.920
Richard: How can I help?
She needs to be ruled out

16:36.920 --> 16:38.960
of multi-organ damage,
hypertensive ICH.

16:38.960 --> 16:40.120
I've started her
on a clevidipine drip.

16:40.120 --> 16:42.080
Hunt,
you need to step away.

16:42.080 --> 16:43.120
We need that X-ray
in here now!

16:43.120 --> 16:44.460
Let me do this!

16:44.460 --> 16:46.420
Just...call Amelia.

16:46.420 --> 16:47.830
Tell her
that Betty's back.

16:47.830 --> 16:49.460
We don't need her to
flip her car trying to get here.

16:51.750 --> 16:53.120
Richard, please.

16:55.750 --> 16:57.710
[ Monitor beeping ]

16:57.710 --> 16:59.120
[ Sighs ]

16:59.120 --> 17:01.420
♪♪

17:03.750 --> 17:05.120
I need to be
with Betty.

17:05.120 --> 17:07.250
No, you need hydration,
and we need to observe --

17:07.250 --> 17:08.540
One of the first nights
at rehab,

17:08.540 --> 17:10.580
Betty was telling me
what she's scared of.

17:10.580 --> 17:13.540
I-I-It was blood,
being home alone in the dark,

17:13.540 --> 17:15.580
falling into
a frozen lake,

17:15.580 --> 17:17.670
a-and she was scared
that for the rest of her life,

17:17.670 --> 17:18.880
she'd have to
tell people

17:18.880 --> 17:22.210
that her dealer
got her pregnant at 15.

17:22.210 --> 17:23.830
And who would
love her then?

17:23.830 --> 17:24.960
But I did.
All right?

17:24.960 --> 17:26.330
And I do.

17:26.330 --> 17:28.540
And I told her that one day,
we'd get a house

17:28.540 --> 17:30.330
and that we could
keep the lights on all the time

17:30.330 --> 17:31.790
and we'd be
nowhere near a lake

17:31.790 --> 17:34.170
and that no matter what,
I would love her.

17:34.170 --> 17:35.210
No matter what.

17:35.210 --> 17:36.580
You have to save her --
please.

17:36.580 --> 17:38.040
Betty's getting
the help she needs.

17:39.830 --> 17:42.120
I'll...get you an update
as soon as I can.

17:46.920 --> 17:49.420
Okay, Ralph,
I've paged a plastic surgeon

17:49.420 --> 17:51.080
to come take a look
at these skin lesions.

17:51.080 --> 17:52.750
[ Laughs ]

17:52.750 --> 17:54.960
I don't have any shoes,
but I'm getting plastic surgery.

17:54.960 --> 17:56.250
[ Chuckles ]

17:56.250 --> 17:58.170
And I'll need
a urine sample.

17:58.170 --> 17:59.580
What for?

17:59.580 --> 18:01.580
We just need to run
a tox screen.

18:01.580 --> 18:03.210
Oh, that's unnecessary.

18:03.210 --> 18:06.290
I don't do drugs
or drink alcohol.

18:06.290 --> 18:07.880
I just make my home
in the park.

18:07.880 --> 18:10.040
I'm not like them.

18:10.040 --> 18:12.120
They're bringing down
the neighborhood, you ask me.

18:14.540 --> 18:16.920
Do you have...anywhere else
that you could stay?

18:16.920 --> 18:18.330
A temporary shelter?

18:18.330 --> 18:20.420
No. They got more people
than they got beds.

18:20.420 --> 18:22.790
They set a limit
on how many nights you can stay.

18:22.790 --> 18:25.460
I maxed out months ago.

18:25.460 --> 18:28.920
I never thought I'd be
calling a park bench my home,

18:28.920 --> 18:31.790
but rent control went out,
and I went out with it.

18:33.420 --> 18:34.960
Jackson: [ Sighs ]

18:34.960 --> 18:35.830
Qadri,
what do we have?

18:35.830 --> 18:37.500
This is Mr. Tennyson.

18:37.500 --> 18:39.880
He's got ulcerations and eschars
on the dorsums of his feet.

18:39.880 --> 18:43.250
Mr. Tennyson, this is Dr. Avery.
He's our head of plastics.

18:43.250 --> 18:45.120
You don't want to give me
a nose job, do you?

18:45.120 --> 18:46.460
[ Laughs ]

18:46.460 --> 18:48.750
No, sir.
Your nose is perfect.

18:48.750 --> 18:50.500
I would like to take a look
at these feet, though.

18:52.960 --> 18:54.790
Qadri, face.

18:54.790 --> 18:56.420
[ Clears throat ]

18:56.750 --> 18:59.790
[ Monitor beeping ]

18:59.790 --> 19:01.620
Teddy: She's got
a widened mediastinum,

19:01.620 --> 19:03.120
and with the meth
and opioids --

19:03.120 --> 19:04.540
You're worried
about an aortic dissection.

19:04.540 --> 19:06.040
Mm-hmm.

19:06.040 --> 19:08.040
Richard: It's a known
complication of meth.

19:08.040 --> 19:09.750
She's got
the classic signs.

19:13.880 --> 19:15.000
Hey. Where is she?

19:15.000 --> 19:16.500
Amelia --

19:16.500 --> 19:18.000
Well, is she hurt or just high?
Richard said --

19:18.000 --> 19:19.880
Listen, I didn't want you
to panic,

19:19.880 --> 19:22.250
but we received some patients
from Meridien Park,

19:22.250 --> 19:23.330
and they all OD'd
from the same drug --

19:23.330 --> 19:25.620
She OD'd?
Is she okay?

19:25.620 --> 19:26.710
You brought them here?

19:26.710 --> 19:29.000
They were still
at the house.

19:29.000 --> 19:30.830
That's Britney.
Britney?

19:30.830 --> 19:32.670
Carol: Oh, my God.
What happened? Is she hurt?
I need to see her. Move.

19:32.670 --> 19:33.920
Owen: You can't go in there.
You can't go --

19:33.920 --> 19:35.170
Oh, my God.
You had to intubate her?

19:35.170 --> 19:36.170
You can't go in there
right now --

19:36.170 --> 19:37.210
That is our daughter!

19:37.210 --> 19:38.620
Yeah, and I'm her doctor,
okay? So --

19:38.620 --> 19:41.080
Okay, everyone calm down
and let Dr. Altman do her work.

19:41.080 --> 19:42.330
You too, Hunt.

19:42.330 --> 19:43.420
Okay, just tell us
what happened.

19:43.420 --> 19:45.960
She, uh, complained
about chest pain,

19:45.960 --> 19:48.500
and it looks like
she's had an aortic dissection.

19:48.500 --> 19:49.790
We're prepping her
for the O.R. right now.

19:49.790 --> 19:51.380
Surgery?

19:51.380 --> 19:53.290
We're gonna call Pierce,
we're gonna meet her there.

19:53.290 --> 19:55.210
I'm gonna do it.
No, no.
You have an entire E.R. --

19:55.210 --> 19:56.790
Bailey can handle it.
No.
I'm gonna call Pierce --

19:56.790 --> 19:57.880
We don't have time
to wait for Pierce.

19:57.880 --> 19:59.120
Owen, let her do it.

20:00.500 --> 20:01.830
Okay.

20:01.830 --> 20:03.080
Well, I'm gonna go, too.

20:03.080 --> 20:05.330
Uh, Dr. Hunt, now,
you can help out in the pit,

20:05.330 --> 20:07.170
or you can sit in the chair
with the other parents,

20:07.170 --> 20:09.250
but you will not step one foot
in that O.R.

20:09.250 --> 20:11.170
[ Baby crying ]
Teddy:
All right, here we go.

20:11.170 --> 20:12.750
All right.
Watch the baby, please.

20:12.750 --> 20:13.540
Here we come.

20:13.540 --> 20:14.830
Thank you.

20:14.830 --> 20:15.620
Hold the elevator!

20:15.620 --> 20:23.330
♪♪

20:23.330 --> 20:25.750
I don't understand
why you took him. He was fine.

20:25.750 --> 20:27.620
Because he was out of your sight
for a little while,

20:27.620 --> 20:28.830
so we just needed
to check him out.

20:28.830 --> 20:30.580
He'll be back soon.

20:30.580 --> 20:32.960
You know, let me -- let me
take your blood pressure again.

20:32.960 --> 20:34.250
I'm fine!

20:34.250 --> 20:35.380
And so is he.

20:35.380 --> 20:37.120
We should
just be able to go.

20:37.120 --> 20:38.120
Okay.

20:40.500 --> 20:41.790
Stuart?

20:41.790 --> 20:43.580
Oh, my God!

20:43.580 --> 20:46.210
Honey, they didn't need
to call you.

20:46.210 --> 20:47.500
We just had
a little scare.

20:47.500 --> 20:50.330
Wendy, tell me
what the hell is going on.

20:50.330 --> 20:52.000
I just...

20:52.000 --> 20:54.670
Rita gave me some pills once,
from her back surgery,

20:54.670 --> 20:55.920
just...to relax me.

20:55.920 --> 20:58.330
You were in the park
to buy drugs?

20:58.330 --> 21:00.080
You took Truman with you
to buy drugs?

21:01.580 --> 21:05.170
I couldn't leave him alone
in the car.

21:05.170 --> 21:08.080
[ Voice breaking ]
Please, Stuart. I'm sorry.

21:08.080 --> 21:10.460
I love him.
I love him.

21:10.460 --> 21:13.170
I love him!
You have to forgive me!

21:13.170 --> 21:15.250
Can you take me
to my son, please?

21:15.250 --> 21:16.580
[ Crying ] Please.

21:16.580 --> 21:19.040
♪♪

21:19.040 --> 21:20.170
[ Sighs ]

21:20.170 --> 21:21.540
[ Door closes ]

21:21.540 --> 21:26.580
♪♪

21:26.580 --> 21:28.080
[ Sighs ]

21:29.880 --> 21:30.960
[ Exhales sharply ]

21:32.580 --> 21:34.040
It's a lot, right?

21:34.040 --> 21:37.620
This is one of those days
where being a doctor is...

21:37.620 --> 21:40.080
[ Sighs ]
It feels futile.

21:40.080 --> 21:41.380
It's, like,
we're in here

21:41.380 --> 21:43.460
doing our damnedest
to save lives, and out there,

21:43.460 --> 21:45.790
people are just
killing themselves or each other

21:45.790 --> 21:49.040
faster than we can
possibly work, so...

21:49.040 --> 21:50.670
[ Sighs ]
...what's the point?

21:55.420 --> 21:56.670
Where would you go?

21:58.290 --> 22:00.670
If you just...
gave it all up?

22:00.670 --> 22:02.790
Um...

22:02.790 --> 22:04.500
You know, when it all
seems hopeless,

22:04.500 --> 22:08.000
what's your secret
fantasy escape hatch?

22:08.000 --> 22:12.040
♪♪

22:12.040 --> 22:13.460
Went to Barbados once.

22:13.460 --> 22:17.170
It was a bunch of expats --
started a Blues bar.

22:18.420 --> 22:22.670
Tiny little shack
but incredible guitar players.

22:22.670 --> 22:25.960
Waves...rum...sand...

22:25.960 --> 22:27.120
quiet.

22:29.380 --> 22:30.290
You?

22:33.000 --> 22:35.170
Right now,
that sounds...

22:35.170 --> 22:36.670
pretty great, actually.

22:36.670 --> 22:39.080
♪♪

22:39.080 --> 22:40.620
[ Thud ]

22:40.620 --> 22:41.420
What the --

22:42.960 --> 22:44.080
What's --

22:45.500 --> 22:46.750
Oh, my God.
Son of a bitch!

22:46.750 --> 22:47.790
Oh, my God.

22:47.790 --> 22:48.790
Oh, my God, no.

22:48.790 --> 22:50.080
Here.

22:50.080 --> 22:51.670
Got to get down here.

22:51.670 --> 22:54.080
[ Water running ]

22:56.620 --> 22:57.880
[ Door opens ]

22:57.880 --> 22:59.830
I came
as soon as I heard --

22:59.830 --> 23:01.210
Type B dissection?

23:01.210 --> 23:04.000
I'm gonna do an endovascular
stent of the descending aorta.

23:04.000 --> 23:05.380
Webber's on his way up
to join.

23:05.380 --> 23:07.170
Thank you. I know you've been
swamped down in the pit.

23:07.170 --> 23:08.620
I can take it from here.

23:08.620 --> 23:10.500
No.
No?

23:10.500 --> 23:13.290
She's so pale, I can see
every capillary under her skin.

23:13.290 --> 23:15.580
That dissection could
cause her aorta to rupture.

23:17.460 --> 23:20.080
You know as well I do
that Amelia may never see

23:20.080 --> 23:22.080
that little girl
open her eyes again.

23:22.080 --> 23:24.210
Teddy --
And if that happens,

23:24.210 --> 23:26.460
let me be the surgeon
to tell Amelia that we lost her.

23:26.460 --> 23:28.710
Because she's gonna need
her sister.

23:28.710 --> 23:34.710
♪♪

23:34.710 --> 23:40.920
♪♪

23:46.120 --> 23:48.750
[ Sighs ]
You are so close.

23:48.750 --> 23:50.080
Tell me something.

23:50.080 --> 23:52.250
Okay. What?

23:52.250 --> 23:53.330
Just anything.

23:53.330 --> 23:54.620
Because all I can
think about right now

23:54.620 --> 23:56.460
is how much
my feet and my legs hurt,

23:56.460 --> 23:58.500
so if you tell me something,
I can think about that instead.

23:58.500 --> 24:00.710
Um, okay.

24:00.710 --> 24:04.120
Uh, when I was seven years old,
I broke a world record.

24:05.420 --> 24:07.250
For what?

24:07.250 --> 24:10.170
Most times a minor rode
a roller coaster in one day.

24:10.170 --> 24:12.620
Really? How many times
did you ride it?

24:12.620 --> 24:13.460
12.

24:15.420 --> 24:17.330
I-I didn't really break
a world record,

24:17.330 --> 24:18.830
but for several years,
I believed that I did.

24:18.830 --> 24:20.210
[ Both laugh ]

24:22.670 --> 24:25.420
♪ You flood my mind ♪

24:25.420 --> 24:27.670
♪ When I dive in too deep ♪

24:27.670 --> 24:29.210
You're an artist.

24:29.210 --> 24:31.540
And I think
it didn't occur to me

24:31.540 --> 24:33.540
because you're also
a work of art.

24:33.540 --> 24:35.000
[ Laughs ]

24:35.000 --> 24:36.380
Physically.

24:36.380 --> 24:39.170
Like a statue in Rome.

24:39.170 --> 24:41.380
And [Laughs]
when I look at you,

24:41.380 --> 24:44.750
surgery isn't
what springs to mind.

24:44.750 --> 24:46.170
But that...

24:46.170 --> 24:47.620
♪ I don't speak my mind
out loud ♪

24:47.620 --> 24:50.330
...in there...

24:50.330 --> 24:52.120
♪ It might not seem like
I am listening ♪

24:52.120 --> 24:53.380
I want to be
that good.

24:55.540 --> 24:58.120
You'll get there.

24:58.120 --> 25:00.830
[ Whispering ] And you're also
good at a lot of things.

25:00.830 --> 25:03.380
♪ Mmm ♪

25:03.380 --> 25:05.790
So much better
than a comic book.

25:05.790 --> 25:07.290
♪♪

25:07.290 --> 25:09.330
♪ To feel nothing ♪

25:09.330 --> 25:13.170
♪♪

25:13.170 --> 25:18.500
♪ I'm hardwired differently ♪

25:18.500 --> 25:19.500
[ Sighs ]

25:19.500 --> 25:20.710
Couldn't get him back.

25:20.710 --> 25:22.330
He was my patient.

25:22.330 --> 25:24.920
I left him sitting in a bed
with an IV in his arm.

25:24.920 --> 25:26.960
Perfectly healthy kid.

25:31.040 --> 25:33.790
Dr. Shepherd?

25:33.790 --> 25:37.460
Are you okay?

25:37.460 --> 25:40.710
Do you want to take a break,
take a walk?

25:40.710 --> 25:43.210
I knew him.

25:43.210 --> 25:45.380
That kid.

25:45.380 --> 25:46.330
He was, uh...

25:48.750 --> 25:50.710
He was a good kid.

25:50.710 --> 25:52.960
He wasn't a bad kid.

25:56.460 --> 25:57.790
I'm gonna have to
call his parents.

26:00.000 --> 26:01.420
I can take care
of that.

26:01.420 --> 26:02.420
No.

26:03.790 --> 26:05.210
No, I'm...

26:06.500 --> 26:07.540
Thank you.

26:11.380 --> 26:13.170
[ Sobbing ]

26:17.960 --> 26:19.250
[ Moans ]

26:21.080 --> 26:23.670
[ Sniffles ]

26:23.670 --> 26:24.710
I'm so sorry.

26:24.710 --> 26:26.380
It's -- It's okay.

26:26.380 --> 26:27.580
[ Voice breaking ]
I'm so sorry.

26:27.580 --> 26:30.210
[ Sobbing ]

26:35.790 --> 26:37.540
Great work, Qadri.

26:37.540 --> 26:40.830
You want to cut away
all that dead tissue

26:40.830 --> 26:42.960
till we find
healthy bleeding.

26:42.960 --> 26:43.960
Almost done.

26:43.960 --> 26:45.040
So I get to keep 'em?

26:45.040 --> 26:46.290
You do
get to keep them.

26:51.290 --> 26:53.080
Can I talk to you?

26:53.080 --> 26:54.290
Yeah, of course.

26:54.290 --> 26:55.580
[ Sighs ]

26:55.580 --> 26:57.380
I can't go camping
this weekend.

26:57.380 --> 26:58.710
Babe, see,
the thing is you think

26:58.710 --> 27:00.170
you can't go camping
this weekend, okay?

27:00.170 --> 27:01.290
But once
we get out there,

27:01.290 --> 27:03.040
you're gonna find it
breathtaking.

27:03.040 --> 27:05.380
And you will realize
all the things we
don't need in life --

27:05.380 --> 27:07.210
just how much
we don't need, okay?

27:07.210 --> 27:09.000
When you're sitting there
by a fire crackling,

27:09.000 --> 27:10.920
one bowl, one spoon,
you realize

27:10.920 --> 27:13.080
we don't need...
three pairs of ski boots.

27:13.080 --> 27:14.750
You know?

27:14.750 --> 27:16.210
Y-- No.
And don't -- don't tell me
that you don't ski.

27:16.210 --> 27:18.080
I know you don't ski,
because it's outdoors,

27:18.080 --> 27:19.710
but that's probably
because your parents

27:19.710 --> 27:22.210
didn't take you outdoors,
but when I do, you will see.

27:22.210 --> 27:24.710
Okay? Just let me show you,
please? Okay?

27:24.710 --> 27:26.000
Okay.
Backing up...

27:26.000 --> 27:27.170
Mm-hmm.

27:27.170 --> 27:28.710
Betty is
in the hospital.

27:28.710 --> 27:30.290
She OD'd.

27:30.290 --> 27:32.620
Amelia's gonna need help,
so --

27:32.620 --> 27:34.790
So you cannot go camping
this weekend.

27:34.790 --> 27:36.670
My bad.

27:36.670 --> 27:38.380
I'm sorry.

27:38.380 --> 27:40.040
You should still go,
though.

27:42.330 --> 27:44.210
Aw. That's too bad.

27:45.750 --> 27:48.040
Ah, it's okay.

27:48.040 --> 27:49.500
[ Clears throat ]
Next time.

27:51.000 --> 27:54.580
Okay, so, we're
almost finished here.

27:54.580 --> 27:56.250
I'll get you
bandaged up.

27:56.250 --> 27:58.380
It's important that you keep
this clean and dry, okay?

27:58.380 --> 27:59.960
That'll be tricky.

27:59.960 --> 28:01.460
Ralph lives in the park.

28:01.460 --> 28:03.500
He brought in
a little missing boy today.

28:03.500 --> 28:04.790
Oh.

28:04.790 --> 28:06.080
The park.

28:06.080 --> 28:08.920
Okay, I hadn't...
realized that.

28:08.920 --> 28:10.790
It's okay.

28:10.790 --> 28:13.080
Makes you realize
all the things you don't need.

28:16.330 --> 28:18.000
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Teller to the E.R.

28:18.000 --> 28:20.880
Dr. Teller to the E.R.

28:20.880 --> 28:22.540
Mr. Cole.

28:22.540 --> 28:24.750
The police have taken your wife
into custody and --

28:24.750 --> 28:27.620
Good.
The police can have her.

28:27.620 --> 28:30.710
Sir, your wife has a problem.
She needs treatment.

28:30.710 --> 28:32.250
She needs that
more than punishment.

28:32.250 --> 28:33.540
I don't know
what I can do for her.

28:33.540 --> 28:35.540
No, you're right.
Don't worry about her.

28:35.540 --> 28:37.040
Worry about him.

28:37.040 --> 28:39.830
And no matter what she says,
you don't just forgive her.

28:39.830 --> 28:42.080
You don't let her near him
until you know she's clean.

28:42.080 --> 28:44.670
Yes, get her treatment,
but protect your kid.

28:44.670 --> 28:46.670
You got me?

28:46.670 --> 28:48.290
Protect your kid.

28:48.290 --> 28:54.170
♪♪

28:54.170 --> 28:56.580
Teddy:
Okay, let's shoot the angio.

28:56.580 --> 28:59.920
No endoleaks, stent-grafts
are well-approximated.

28:59.920 --> 29:01.750
Aortic arch is clear.

29:01.750 --> 29:03.210
There's no flow
from the celiac.

29:03.210 --> 29:04.500
Let's shoot
from the femoral.

29:05.540 --> 29:07.460
Dye.

29:07.460 --> 29:13.330
♪♪

29:13.330 --> 29:15.420
Higher concentration
of dye.

29:15.420 --> 29:17.830
God, I hate
that she did this to herself.

29:17.830 --> 29:19.670
That's addiction --
the thing that's killing you

29:19.670 --> 29:22.330
keeps whispering in your ear
that you need it to survive.

29:24.250 --> 29:25.750
There's no flow
from either end.

29:25.750 --> 29:27.830
Her distal aorta
is blocked.

29:27.830 --> 29:29.460
Which means
there's no blood flow

29:29.460 --> 29:30.830
to the distal
extremities.

29:30.830 --> 29:32.040
Damn it! Damn it!

29:32.040 --> 29:33.670
Altman, if there's
any extraordinary measures

29:33.670 --> 29:36.750
you can use here,
please use them now.

29:36.750 --> 29:38.250
Okay.
Take everything out.

29:38.250 --> 29:39.540
We're gonna have to
open her up

29:39.540 --> 29:41.880
and reconstruct
her distal aorta completely

29:41.880 --> 29:43.120
if we're gonna
save her life.

29:43.120 --> 29:44.210
Let me have a pad.

29:44.210 --> 29:45.880
All right,
let's prep her abdomen!

29:45.880 --> 29:47.540
Let's go. Come on.

29:47.540 --> 29:49.080
Come on, Betty.
Come on.

29:56.380 --> 29:58.420
I can't even stand
to look at you.

30:01.080 --> 30:04.250
That's the last thing I said
to her before she disappeared.

30:07.330 --> 30:09.380
"I can't even stand
to look at you."

30:12.790 --> 30:14.460
[ Inhales sharply ]

30:14.460 --> 30:15.790
Now...

30:15.790 --> 30:17.710
[ Gulps, exhales ]

30:17.710 --> 30:21.120
♪♪

30:21.120 --> 30:23.170
Tell us
that she's gonna be okay.

30:24.830 --> 30:26.330
I mean, you're doctors.
Just...

30:28.460 --> 30:30.000
...tell us that she's gonna
get through this.

30:32.420 --> 30:33.670
I wish I could.

30:36.120 --> 30:38.290
I wish
I could tell you that.

30:43.750 --> 30:47.330
♪ Where are you now ♪

30:47.330 --> 30:51.120
♪ When darkness seems to win? ♪

30:51.120 --> 30:54.210
♪♪

30:54.210 --> 30:55.620
DeLuca, you'll place
the wound vac.

30:55.620 --> 30:56.920
Okay.

30:56.920 --> 30:59.620
Final time --
27 hours and 8 minutes.

30:59.620 --> 31:03.330
That beats the hospital's
old record by over three hours.

31:03.330 --> 31:04.250
Whoo!

31:06.500 --> 31:08.080
Thank you for the assist,
Dr. DeLuca.

31:08.080 --> 31:10.080
♪ I hear you say ♪

31:10.080 --> 31:12.210
♪ I hear you say ♪

31:12.210 --> 31:15.040
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

31:15.040 --> 31:18.380
♪ Mm-hmm, hey, hey ♪

31:18.380 --> 31:21.000
I am going to go put my feet
in medical waste,

31:21.000 --> 31:22.790
so I definitely need
a ride home.

31:22.790 --> 31:24.670
Amelia needs us.

31:24.670 --> 31:26.540
It's Betty.

31:26.540 --> 31:28.040
She's gonna need us.

31:31.040 --> 31:33.120
♪ Where are you now ♪

31:33.120 --> 31:34.670
[ Sniffles, sighs ]

31:34.670 --> 31:38.330
♪ When darkness seems to win? ♪

31:41.540 --> 31:43.620
♪ Where are you now ♪

31:43.620 --> 31:44.920
[ Door opens ]

31:44.920 --> 31:47.170
Mr. and Mrs. Dickinson?

31:47.170 --> 31:49.250
She's out of surgery.

31:49.250 --> 31:50.620
She's being moved
up to the ICU.

31:50.620 --> 31:52.620
♪ Oh, I ♪

31:52.620 --> 31:54.540
♪ I ♪

31:54.540 --> 31:57.210
♪ I hear you say ♪

31:57.210 --> 31:59.960
♪ I hear you say ♪

31:59.960 --> 32:02.120
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

32:02.120 --> 32:03.710
♪♪

32:03.710 --> 32:05.000
♪ Hey ♪

32:05.000 --> 32:07.540
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

32:08.790 --> 32:10.080
♪ Hey ♪

32:13.250 --> 32:15.250
♪ Where are you now ♪

32:15.250 --> 32:17.500
Oh, thank God.

32:17.500 --> 32:20.920
That means...
she made it, right?

32:20.920 --> 32:22.540
Yeah.

32:22.540 --> 32:24.460
I think
that's what that means.

32:24.460 --> 32:27.620
♪ Where are you now ♪

32:27.620 --> 32:31.120
♪ When I can't figure it out? ♪

32:31.120 --> 32:32.710
[ Chuckles softly ]

32:32.710 --> 32:34.790
♪ Oh, I ♪

32:34.790 --> 32:37.170
♪ I ♪

32:37.170 --> 32:39.920
♪ I hear you say ♪

32:39.920 --> 32:41.920
♪ I hear you say ♪

32:41.920 --> 32:43.670
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

32:43.670 --> 32:44.670
[ Groans ]

32:44.670 --> 32:45.750
Come here.

32:45.750 --> 32:47.290
♪ Hey ♪

32:47.290 --> 32:49.080
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

32:49.080 --> 32:52.210
[ Sighs ]
This world is so scary.

32:52.210 --> 32:54.580
No matter how well
you raise your kids,

32:54.580 --> 32:56.750
no matter
how much give them,

32:56.750 --> 32:59.460
it's a scary,
scary world.

32:59.460 --> 33:01.000
Yeah.

33:01.000 --> 33:02.920
It is.

33:02.920 --> 33:04.460
But it's beautiful, too.
Mm.

33:04.460 --> 33:07.880
And if you descend into the fear
and miss the beauty,

33:07.880 --> 33:10.080
that's when you start to go
to a bad place

33:10.080 --> 33:13.420
and need to...escape.

33:13.420 --> 33:14.750
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

33:14.750 --> 33:16.500
I'm not gonna start
using drugs.

33:16.500 --> 33:18.540
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah, I know.

33:18.540 --> 33:21.460
But...just...

33:21.460 --> 33:24.210
be in the beauty with me
for a second.

33:24.210 --> 33:26.420
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

33:26.420 --> 33:28.080
♪ I hear you say ♪

33:28.080 --> 33:29.420
♪ Ohh ♪

33:29.420 --> 33:32.460
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

33:32.460 --> 33:33.750
♪ Ooh, ooh, hey ♪

33:33.750 --> 33:34.920
♪ Hey ♪

33:34.920 --> 33:37.670
♪ "Look up, child" ♪

33:37.670 --> 33:39.540
♪ Ooh, ooh, hey, look up ♪

33:39.540 --> 33:42.500
And you don't have room
for one -- just one more?

33:42.500 --> 33:44.710
He's a 75-year-old m--

33:44.710 --> 33:46.040
His f--

33:47.420 --> 33:48.540
Mm-hmm.

33:49.920 --> 33:51.960
Y-- Yeah. I --

33:51.960 --> 33:54.620
No, I understand.

33:54.620 --> 33:55.710
Thank you.

33:56.670 --> 33:57.920
No luck?

33:57.920 --> 33:59.460
It should not be
this difficult

33:59.460 --> 34:01.210
to find a place to stay
for an elderly man.

34:01.210 --> 34:02.710
No, it shouldn't.
[ Sighs ]

34:04.120 --> 34:05.830
I feel awful.

34:05.830 --> 34:07.420
I mean, I was going on and on
about how we can't decide

34:07.420 --> 34:08.790
whether we should
stay inside or outside,

34:08.790 --> 34:09.920
and I've got too many --

34:09.920 --> 34:11.330
Ski boots.

34:11.330 --> 34:12.500
Thank you.
Yeah.

34:12.500 --> 34:15.250
And I spent all day
debriding his feet,

34:15.250 --> 34:17.080
and there's no way he can
maintain a follow-up protocol

34:17.080 --> 34:18.330
on a park bench.

34:18.330 --> 34:19.750
[ Sighs ]

34:19.750 --> 34:21.790
I would say just cook his chart
and keep him another night,

34:21.790 --> 34:23.710
but then where is he gonna go
tomorrow night?

34:32.080 --> 34:33.710
Owen took Leo
to daycare

34:33.710 --> 34:35.960
so that you could focus
on Britney.

34:37.750 --> 34:39.710
So, how are we
gonna tell her?

34:39.710 --> 34:41.040
About her...boyfriend?

34:41.040 --> 34:42.540
[ Voice breaking ]
How are we gonna tell her?

34:42.540 --> 34:43.920
We don't tell her.

34:45.380 --> 34:46.500
What?

34:46.500 --> 34:47.880
No.

34:47.880 --> 34:49.710
We don't tell her.

34:49.710 --> 34:51.880
I'm afraid something like that,
that would kill her.

34:51.880 --> 34:54.540
That kind of...news
could --

34:54.540 --> 34:55.710
it could kill her.

34:59.540 --> 35:01.790
My fiancé died.

35:01.790 --> 35:05.040
Um...years ago.

35:05.040 --> 35:07.500
He died in bed
beside me.

35:07.500 --> 35:09.880
He OD'd.

35:09.880 --> 35:11.920
I thought
it would kill me, too.

35:11.920 --> 35:13.880
But instead,
it saved my life.

35:16.920 --> 35:18.960
Because I decided to live.

35:21.170 --> 35:23.000
I decided to live
because he died.

35:26.250 --> 35:29.580
You can't protect her
from this.

35:29.580 --> 35:31.250
You can't protect her
from the pain

35:31.250 --> 35:33.080
that she is going to feel.

35:35.000 --> 35:37.540
But you can hope...

35:37.540 --> 35:40.420
that this is her bottom.

35:40.420 --> 35:42.670
I...

35:42.670 --> 35:44.830
[ Exhales shakily ]
God, I hope this is her bottom.

35:46.460 --> 35:48.000
I hope this gets her clean.

35:52.750 --> 35:54.500
I hope
that she decides to live.

35:54.500 --> 36:01.710
♪♪

36:01.710 --> 36:04.380
Please decide to live.

36:04.380 --> 36:06.920
Honey,
please decide to live.

36:06.920 --> 36:11.580
♪♪

36:11.580 --> 36:14.960
♪ How I marveled at your pace ♪

36:14.960 --> 36:16.330
Are you sure?

36:16.330 --> 36:18.460
Yeah.
Yeah, whatever you want.

36:18.460 --> 36:20.500
It's not much, but it's enough
to keep you warm and dry

36:20.500 --> 36:22.790
till you get off the waitlist
for a real place.

36:22.790 --> 36:25.750
Dry socks here, long underwear,
lightweight tent,

36:25.750 --> 36:28.040
a sleeping bag,
a couple raincoats,

36:28.040 --> 36:29.170
and a pair of shoes for you

36:29.170 --> 36:30.620
once the swelling goes down
a bit.

36:30.620 --> 36:34.330
You had all this...
just in the trunk of your car?

36:34.330 --> 36:36.880
[ Sighs ]

36:36.880 --> 36:37.920
Yeah.

36:39.210 --> 36:41.000
Yeah, I did.

36:41.000 --> 36:44.580
♪ And I will bide my time
for you ♪

36:47.460 --> 36:49.170
[ Clears throat ]

36:49.170 --> 36:51.120
[ Sighs ]

36:52.790 --> 36:55.380
You were left
in a park, right?

36:55.380 --> 36:57.500
When you were three.

36:57.500 --> 36:59.170
By your junkie dad.

37:01.170 --> 37:02.620
Bar parking lot.

37:02.620 --> 37:04.790
And I was six.

37:04.790 --> 37:07.000
I wish I'd been three.

37:07.000 --> 37:10.460
Then I wouldn't have remembered
that he left me there.

37:10.460 --> 37:13.750
♪♪

37:13.750 --> 37:14.710
[ Clears throat ]

37:16.120 --> 37:17.830
Jo, it's too late
for coffee.

37:17.830 --> 37:19.830
It's hot chocolate.

37:19.830 --> 37:21.540
I am not a kid anymore.

37:21.540 --> 37:22.830
Oh.

37:22.830 --> 37:24.330
I am the chief.

37:24.330 --> 37:30.460
♪♪

37:30.460 --> 37:32.380
Mmm.
Yeah, that's good.

37:32.380 --> 37:34.120
[ Laughs ]
It's really good.

37:35.620 --> 37:36.920
I love you.

37:38.790 --> 37:39.830
I love you.

37:41.670 --> 37:44.000
Meredith: They call it a high
for a reason.

37:44.000 --> 37:46.670
♪♪

37:46.670 --> 37:48.750
Because the flip side
is really low.

37:50.670 --> 37:53.960
♪ And I thank you
for letting me watch you fall ♪

37:53.960 --> 37:55.210
[ Groans ]

37:56.880 --> 37:58.670
[ Sighs ]

37:58.670 --> 38:03.210
♪ I thank you
for letting me watch you fall ♪

38:03.210 --> 38:06.080
[ Monitor beeping ]

38:06.080 --> 38:09.960
♪ And I will bide my time
for you ♪

38:09.960 --> 38:13.380
♪♪

38:13.380 --> 38:15.250
♪ And I will bide my time... ♪

38:15.250 --> 38:16.580
Mom?

38:16.580 --> 38:18.170
I'm here.

38:19.790 --> 38:21.750
I'm here.

38:21.750 --> 38:26.120
